AGI - European unity, climate change, European social pillar and defence of democracy. These are some of the themes that the King Philip of Belgi addressed in his speech in the plenary of the European Parliament in Brussels. "Here, in Brussels, the European institutions have found their home from the beginning," he began in the Chamber. "Even personally I feel very strong this connection with Europe, not only as head of state and as Belgian, but also as a human being. The family tree of my family is a testament to the historical intersection of European nations," he added.
&nbsp;
"The colorful legacy of our ancestors and the experiences we acquire along the way make us what we are. This versatile layering and interweaving of cultures is a huge enrichment. They link us to the fate of others, encourage us to leave a stable and prosperous world," he continued. "In these times of war, uncertainty and social disorders, Europe and the world have a desperate need for hope," the sovereign continued.
&nbsp;
"Divisions within the Union are often discussed. But by supporting Ukraine we demonstrate that together we can make strong decisions," the monarch recalled, citing also the crisis situations posed by Brexit and Covid-19. "In every crisis, in every turn, we show ourselves united and decisive. But the European Union goes far beyond the simple management of crises >: it must lead a long-term vision," he said. The European unity, according to Philip, must first express itself in the work of combating climate change. "Since 1990, the European economy has grown by 60%, while emissions have decreased by 30%.&nbsp; however, there is still a lot to do before reaching targets for 2030 and 2050, and global emissions are unfortunately increasing. Our climate policy also contributes to the realization of another important objective, namely the strategic independence of the Union. The more we use renewable energies, the less we depend on imported energy", he explained.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
"The European Union plays an important geopolitical role in climate issues and is recognized as the geo-ecological actor par excellence," he said. But the unity, according to King Philip, is above all a revolution that replaces national rivalries: "The Union still suffers from excessive fragmentation. Let us imagine a new 'great European revolution of our time, the revolution that aims to replace national rivalries with a union in freedom and diversity', as Jean Monnet proposed. Because the single market of Jacques Delors is not yet sufficiently unified, neither in terms of economic governance, nor in capital markets, nor in research and innovation," he said.
&nbsp;
"There are opportunities to grasp in the areas of electrical mobility, semiconductors, batteries, rare raw materials and artificial intelligence. We are still too often behind invention, but above all in innovation," he said. "One of the main tools to achieve autonomy is to stimulate our competitiveness. We work together for a real European reindustrialization, focused on the green and digital revolution, which represents much more than a simple transition," he pointed out.
<h2> European social dimension
"What distinguishes Europe from other great actors is that the creation of wealth is integrated by important mechanisms of social justice. This complementarity is essential to ensure that young people, tomorrow's citizens, maintain confidence in Europe," he said. In this context, the sovereign was called "worried for the loss of trust" in the European institutions "and the rise of autocracy throughout the world".
&nbsp;
"Democracy is not only guarantor of freedom and justice, but also of human values such as our ability to indignate us in the face of the suffering of people facing inhuman wars. The current global crisis therefore has a moral dimension. The human being must remain the measure of all things," he concluded.

