AGI - In a letter to the top of the Chicago police, the municipal control agency asked for clarifications on the death of Dexter Reed, the 26-year-old African-American motorist killed by agents at a block post, after being stopped for not wearing the seat belt. The cops shot him 96 shots in 41 seconds in what is called a disproportionate reaction. The episode took place on March 21st in a residential area west of Chicago, but only yesterday the images recorded by the body cams supplied to the agents and showing a shocking scene. More details are emerging these hours.
&nbsp;
From the vision of the footage you can see the agents get out of a black suv and without police signs, encircle the white utility of Reed and order him to lower the dark window. One of the cops, wearing jackets and baseball cap, pointing his gun at him and saying, "Put down the window, knock down." And then... "What are you doing?" Reed responds scared: "I'm not doing anything." But the African American begins to raise the glass. "Don't raise the window - I'm telling the cop - don't raise the window." Two more agents approach, both appear armed. One try to open his door. One approaches the car on the opposite side. "Open the door, open the door," he ordered the first. From the images taken from a surveillance camera in the area you see an agent stand on the right side of the car and then shoot >. Smoke comes out of the car, the scene gets confused. An agent would have shot three more shots at the victim, despite already on the ground, face down. A few seconds and everything is over.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
You hear a cop's voice saying he was hurt. Another announces that he found the gun used by the victim in the car, which he would shoot first. Reed, shot at multiple points, was taken to the hospital where he died shortly after. Now these shock images remain and the many doubts that the story takes behind. The carmaker was a former college basketball player who dreamed of becoming a sports journalist. He had two criminals for theft and illegal weapon purchase, but according to the victim's family lawyers all this cannot justify a use of force like that.
&nbsp;
"Why encircle the car for a road violation? Did you ask one of the Reed lawyers, Andrew Stroth, why put the gun in his face? And all this because he didn't wear the seat belt?" The family launched an appeal because these episodes don't happen anymore, but now it wants justice. "We want answers - said Porscha Banks, the victim's older sister - shot him 96 times and reloaded the guns.> All this has to end. I can't explain the pain my family and I are trying." The three agents involved were suspended for thirty days, waiting for the conclusions of the investigation, but it is a normal procedure in these cases. The real result will be seen at the end of the internal investigation. An independent agency will have eighteen months to complete its administrative investigation.
&nbsp;

