AGI - Hamas> told international mediators not to be able to identify and track 40 hostages in life > that they meet the criteria for release in the first stage, > according to the proposal negotiated in Cairo. The Cnn reports it, citing an Israeli official and a source of information about the situation. On the basis of the formula advanced by the negotiators, during a first phase of six weeks the ceasefire would be accompanied by the liberation of 40 hostages, including all women together with wounded and elderly men, in exchange for hundreds of Palestinian prisoners.>&nbsp; Proprio the inability, or reluctance, of Hamas to give Israel a list of hostages in life is a major obstacle, reported a second source quoted by Cnn. In the absence of 40 hostages living in the categories cited for liberation in the first stage, Israel insisted that Hamas enter the list of younger male hostages, including soldiers.
&nbsp;
It is believed that most of the nearly 100 hostages still alive are male soldiers or men at age from military reserve. >Rapiti whose 'weight' the Palestinian group will try to exploit to obtain more significant concessions, including a greater number of high-level prisoners and the permanent end of the war. Meanwhile three of the sons of the head of the political office of Hamas, Ismail Haniyeh>, and some of his grandchildren died in an Israeli attack in Gaza. Al Jazeera reports it. The victims would be 6 in all, including the sons of Hamas' leader: Hazem, Amir and Muhammad Haniyeh>.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
The head of the political office Hamas confirmed the news.> "Through the blood of the martyrs and the pain of the wounded, we create hope, we create the future, we create independence and freedom for our people and our nation", said Haniyeh, who told Al Jazeera that his children were visiting relatives for Eid al Fitr, the feast that marks the end of Ramadan, in the field of Shati, in the north of Gaza, when they were hit. Haniyeh denounced Israel's "brutality" but stressed that Palestinian leaders will not retreat if their families and their homes will be targeted. "There is no doubt that this criminal enemy is guided by the spirit of revenge and the spirit of murder and bloodshed and does not observe any standard or law," said Haniyeh, adding that 60 members of his family were killed from the beginning of the war. According to an Israeli source, Hamas may have failed the negotiations for a hostage settlement due to the murder of Haniyeh's sons.

